b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\r\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\r\n<workbook_page xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/"\r\n\txmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\r\n\txmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\r\n\txmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\r\n\txmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/" id="p2_atomic_mass">\r\n\t<head>\r\n\t\t<title>Atomic Mass</title>\r\n\t\t<objref idref="isotope_mass"/>\r\n\t</head>\r\n\t<body>\r\n\t\t<p id="ab0e1840b36044f2bf6367206b2bb0c5">Because each proton and each neutron contribute\r\n\t\t\tapproximately one amu to the mass of an atom, and each electron contributes far less,\r\n\t\t\tthe <extra><anchor>atomic mass</anchor><meaning><material><p>average mass of atoms of an element, expressed in amu</p></material></meaning></extra> of a single atom is approximately equal to its mass number (a whole\r\n\t\t\tnumber). However, the average masses of atoms of most elements are not whole numbers\r\n\t\t\tbecause most elements exist naturally as mixtures of two or more isotopes.</p>\r\n\t\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t<dl>\r\n\t\t\t<dt><em>Atomic Mass</em></dt>\r\n\t\t\t<dd>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p>The mass of an element shown in a periodic table or listed in a table of atomic\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmasses is a weighted, average mass of all the isotopes present in a naturally\r\n\t\t\t\t\toccurring sample of that element. This is equal to the sum of each individual\r\n\t\t\t\t\tisotope\xe2\x80\x99s mass multiplied by its fractional abundance.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<formula>$$\\mathrm{average}\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;=\\;\\underset{}{\\sum(\\mathrm{fractional}\\;\\mathrm{abundance}\\times\\mathrm{isotopic}\\;\\mathrm{mass})_{}}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t</dd>\r\n\t\t</dl>\r\n\t<image src="../../../webcontent/green_line.png"></image>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<p id="a527981f42764ec1892866e971e7e63f"> For example, the element boron is composed of two\r\n\t\t\tisotopes: About 19.9% of all boron atoms are <sup>10</sup> B with a mass of 10.0129 amu,\r\n\t\t\tand the remaining 80.1% are <sup>11</sup> B with a mass of 11.0093 amu. The average\r\n\t\t\tatomic mass for boron is calculated to be: </p>\r\n\t\t<formula id="fcfd9b713d894f4680e6388045e1275d"\r\n\t\t\t>$$\\mathrm{boron}\\;\\mathrm{average}\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;=\\;(0.199\\;\\times\\;10.0129\\;\\mathrm{amu})\\;+\\;(0.801\\;\\times\\;11.0093\\;\\mathrm{amu})$$</formula>\r\n\t\t<formula id="e34ec6d47ccf4a6faeb3090392f2b2f2"\r\n\t\t\t>$$\\begin{array}{l}=\\;1.99\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;+\\;8.82\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\\\=\\;10.81\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t<p id="b405315da85f4a1fa497463007568399">It is important to understand that no single boron\r\n\t\t\tatom weighs exactly 10.81 amu; 10.81 amu is the average mass of all boron atoms, and\r\n\t\t\tindividual boron atoms weigh either approximately 10 amu or 11 amu.</p>\r\n\t\t<example id="b3d9d2ff92c64c25a97b0204f847a977">\r\n\t\t\t<title/>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="d5949600bf8b4a70b4eea5eedfe69ab9">Silicon exists as 3 isotopes with their masses\r\n\t\t\t\tand abundances listed below.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<table id="f2422884e61540938131ac7b614da85b" summary="" rowstyle="plain">\r\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ff91b76981bc4e4bb7ad39513e9eab47">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Mass Number</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="a8668fb9e8d646d79bb829c6ef560bad">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Exact Weight</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="f2275047cfce4808a0e92a8394dc93a7">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Percent Abundance</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa9f4c74c1e5b4448877dabe31b11d677">28</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ae5d675cc65f543adb848abb9d06bcf8c">27.9769 amu</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac04a537676b14ac2af9311e7db04803c">92.23</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac000379749ab4a739658119acfd91f2b">29</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac554ece76ab94bc396cff3a4c64a9ff9">28.9785 amu</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ad0f1216209de4bd58f7c3d07b5fef9c5">4.67</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab5b7769f0d74469c980a08f1b74b433d">30</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab037864583f447019f01afb7acdeefd3">29.9738 amu</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa37741cfe46c44c3afce419a83a5997a">3.10</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t</table>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="e8c4511ceab146f587e3a58859aad4ff">Calculate the atomic weight from the\r\n\t\t\t\tinformation in the table.</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="fd0df19fd6a04d94bee804ddc64d8647"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\begin{array}{l}=(27.9769\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;\\times\\;0.9223)\\;+\\;(28.9765\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;\\times\\;0.0467)\\;+\\;(29.9738\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;\\times0.0310)\\\\=25.80\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;+\\;1.35\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;+\\;0.929\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\\\=28.08\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="a1ce986df5c447429f806e71b0688a03">While you can easily look up the atomic mass of\r\n\t\t\t\tany element on the periodic table, it is important you understand how the value for\r\n\t\t\t\tthe atomic mass is calculated.</p>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<example id="da378bdbaff44405b7af56af83d9a544">\r\n\t\t\t<title/>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="dc078e81497d403ab0a778bef95d29da"> Naturally occurring chlorine consists of\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<sup>35</sup> Cl (mass 34.96885 amu) and <sup>37</sup> Cl (mass 36.96590 amu),\r\n\t\t\t\twith an average mass of 35.453 amu. What is the percent composition of Cl in terms\r\n\t\t\t\tof these two isotopes? </p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="b9f1379cbb444b8f96d18b8943eb5df7"> The average mass of chlorine is the fraction\r\n\t\t\t\tthat is <sup>35</sup> Cl times the mass of <sup>35</sup> Cl plus the fraction that\r\n\t\t\t\tis <sup>37</sup> Cl times the mass of <sup>37</sup> Cl. </p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="a3ce754df44f4403be9bd8445bd363f3"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\mathrm{avg}\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;=\\;(\\mathrm{fraction}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;{}^{35}\\mathrm{Cl}\\;\\times\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;{}^{35}\\mathrm{Cl})\\;+\\;(\\mathrm{fraction}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;{}^{37}\\mathrm{Cl}\\;\\times\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;{}^{37}\\mathrm{Cl})$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="e6d7be38278f4054bb440b27f9c28b71"> If we let x represent the fraction that is\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<sup>35</sup> Cl, then the fraction that is <sup>37</sup> Cl is represented by\r\n\t\t\t\t1.00 \xe2\x88\x92 x. </p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="b86664577a714c46bf040910e3ae1149"> (The fraction that is <sup>35</sup> Cl + the\r\n\t\t\t\tfraction that is <sup>37</sup> Cl must add up to 1, so the fraction of <sup>37</sup>\r\n\t\t\t\tCl must equal 1.00 \xe2\x88\x92 the fraction of <sup>35</sup> Cl.) </p>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="f13c0df099944a5c804509256546fb49">Substituting this into the average mass\r\n\t\t\t\tequation, we have:</p>\r\n\t\t\t<formula id="a98c2885e9f34af3a1e69a68ea477702"\r\n\t\t\t\t>$$\\begin{array}{l}35.453\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\;=\\;(x\\;\xe2\x8b\x85\\;34.96885\\;\\mathrm{amu})\\;+\\;\\lbrack(1.00\\;-\\;x)\\;\xe2\x8b\x85\\;36.96590\\;\\mathrm{amu}\\rbrack\\\\\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;35.453\\;=\\;34.96885x\\;+\\;36.96590\\;-\\;36.96590x\\\\\\;\\;\\;\\;1.99705x\\;=\\;1.513\\\\\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;x\\;=\\frac{\\;1.513}{1.99705}\\;=\\;0.7576\\end{array}$$</formula>\r\n\t\t\t<p id="ec3121aa766b4adfa3dcee898d0b38cf"> So solving yields: x = 0.7576, which means\r\n\t\t\t\tthat 1.00 \xe2\x88\x92 0.7576 = 0.2424. Therefore, chlorine consists of 75.76% <sup>35</sup> Cl\r\n\t\t\t\tand 24.24% <sup>37</sup> Cl. </p>\r\n\t\t</example>\r\n\t\t<composite_activity purpose="learnbydoing">\r\n\t\t\t<p>In this activity, you will explore the naturally occurring isotopes for two\r\n\t\t\t\telements. Follow the steps and answer the questions that follow. </p>\r\n\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t<iframe\r\n\t\t\t\tsrc="https://phet.colorado.edu/sims/html/isotopes-and-atomic-mass/latest/isotopes-and-atomic-mass_en.html"\r\n\t\t\t\twidth="700" height="525"/>\r\n\t\t\t<p>PhET Interactive Simulations University of Colorado Boulder <link\r\n\t\t\t\thref="https://phet.colorado.edu">https://phet.colorado.edu</link></p>\r\n\t\t\t<p>If you would like to open the simulation in a separate tab, click this link:\r\n\t\t\t\t<activity_link idref="isotope_phet_sim" target="new"><em>Isotopes and Atomic\r\n\t\t\t\t\tMass</em></activity_link></p>\r\n\t\t\t<wb:inline idref="isotope_atomic_mass_1_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t</composite_activity>\r\n\t\t\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="isotope_atomic_mass_2_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\r\n\t\t<wb:inline idref="isotope_atomic_mass_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\r\n\t\t<section id="e86d38c70772485980a8e359624296e6">\r\n\t\t\t<title>Mass Spectrometry (MS)</title>\r\n\t\t\t<body>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="e55c88bbb1374df0897a8c31709832f0">The occurrence and natural abundances of\r\n\t\t\t\t\tisotopes can be experimentally determined using an instrument called a mass\r\n\t\t\t\t\tspectrometer. Mass spectrometry (MS) is widely used in chemistry, forensics,\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmedicine, environmental science, and many other fields to analyze and help\r\n\t\t\t\t\tidentify the substances in a sample of material. In a typical mass spectrometer\r\n\t\t\t\t\t(Figure), the sample is vaporized and exposed to a high-energy electron beam\r\n\t\t\t\t\tthat causes the sample\xe2\x80\x99s atoms (or molecules) to become electrically charged,\r\n\t\t\t\t\ttypically by losing one or more electrons. These cations then pass through a\r\n\t\t\t\t\t(variable) electric or magnetic field that deflects each cation\xe2\x80\x99s path to an\r\n\t\t\t\t\textent that depends on both its mass and charge (similar to how the path of a\r\n\t\t\t\t\tlarge steel ball bearing rolling past a magnet is deflected to a lesser extent\r\n\t\t\t\t\tthan that of a small steel BB). The ions are detected, and a plot of the\r\n\t\t\t\t\trelative number of ions generated versus their mass-to-charge ratios (a mass\r\n\t\t\t\t\tspectrum) is made. The height of each vertical feature or peak in a mass\r\n\t\t\t\t\tspectrum is proportional to the fraction of cations with the specified\r\n\t\t\t\t\tmass-to-charge ratio. Since its initial use during the development of modern\r\n\t\t\t\t\tatomic theory, MS has evolved to become a powerful tool for chemical analysis in\r\n\t\t\t\t\ta wide range of applications.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<image id="be84a42bea7f4387a9b0d57e560d056c"\r\n\t\t\t\t\tsrc="../webcontent/mass_spectrometer.png"\r\n\t\t\t\t\talt="The left diagram shows how a mass spectrometer works, which is primarily a large tube that bends downward at its midpoint. The sample enters on the left side of the tube. A heater heats the sample, causing it to vaporize. The sample is also hit with a beam of electrons as it is being vaporized. Charged particles from the sample, called ions, are then accelerated and pass between two magnets. The magnetic field deflects the lightest ions most. The deflection of the ions is measured by a detector located on the right side of the tube. The graph to the right of the spectrometer shows a mass spectrum of zirconium. The relative abundance, as a percentage from 0 to 100, is graphed on the y axis, and the mass to charge ratio is graphed on the x axis. The sample contains five different isomers of zirconium. Z R 90, which has a mass to charge ratio of 90, is the most abundant isotope at about 51 percent relative abundance. Z R 91 has a mass to charge ratio of 91 and a relative abundance of about 11 percent. Z R 92 has a mass to charge ratio of 92 and a relative abundance of about 18 percent. Z R 94 has a mass to charge ratio of 94 and a relative abundance of about 18 percent. Z R 96, which has a mass to charge ratio of 96, is the least abundant zirconium isotope with a relative abundance of about 2 percent." style="inline"\r\n\t\t\t\t\tvertical-align="middle" width="600">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<caption>Analysis of zirconium in a mass spectrometer produces a mass spectrum\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\twith peaks showing the different isotopes of Zr.</caption>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\r\n\t\t\t\t</image>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="f6b40a31a5144b9db54f0540a6635d15">Based on the information in the mass\r\n\t\t\t\t\tspectra for zirconium in the image above, we can determine that there are 5\r\n\t\t\t\t\tnaturally occurring isotopes of zirconium, Zr\xe2\x88\x9290, Zr\xe2\x88\x9291, Zr\xe2\x88\x9292, Zr\xe2\x88\x9294, and Zr\xe2\x88\x9296\r\n\t\t\t\t\teach with an approximate percent abundance as seen in the table below.</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t<table id="be14a9f00b794e5087dde84f544decc8" summary="" rowstyle="plain">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac26c118b0b04e3796b58c2be61a2932">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Isotope</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="c121ada98f7b478b8b8751a766cadbf9">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<em style="emphasis">Approximate Percent Abundance</em>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="afb4189061e714ea7b54b13bf7afadd97">Zr-90</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="af4746c7941b44e8a9745b92818588d7a">51%</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa7b1436b59414b2da8547e9e83dc8440">Zr-91</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aff52af491e684323b511ed60cef93f48">11%</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ab43c592434134bcd9a74a0225b3a4b54">Zr-91</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="acf34cf11e1a54f84a5e95d4be21b4ae0">17%</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac95d2302f75c4a2aa2df706b0af06d79">Zr-94</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="ac5183139e7634704ba85f34f82e7368e">18%</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="aa81c8314947142b1b9bbe18ae4ab7ba5">Zr-96</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center">\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p id="afdfc63132b13450095637e6f2cc46a23">3%</p>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t\t\t</table>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="f585f015ae8b439497a56742a0b9a123"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="aec907aadbcd14f75a46ec086175dc0ee"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="aeaea71386e7a477fb4203da027917a3d"/>\r\n\t\t\t\t<p id="ad45ddfaddc5e43cbadce85fe4b924a5c">To learn more about mass spectrometry\r\n\t\t\t\t\tclick on the link below